---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const rules = [
  'Fencing matters more than brochure charm.',
  'A clear pet policy matters more than vague “pet friendly” wording.',
  'A stay only really works if there is a walk, beach, or easy dog run nearby.',
  'The best dog-friendly stays still feel like a proper Peninsula trip, not a compromise booking.',
];

const stayTypes = [
  'Self-contained cottages and houses are the strongest dog-friendly category on the Peninsula.',
  'Most better dog stays operate with “dogs inside, but not on furniture” rules.',
  'Outdoor-only pet policies are common and should be stated clearly, not treated as minor fine print.',
  'Holiday-rental style properties generally outperform hotel-style accommodation for dog owners here.',
];
---

<BaseLayout title="Dog-Friendly Accommodation Mornington Peninsula | Peninsula Insider" description="The practical Peninsula Insider guide to dog-friendly accommodation on the Mornington Peninsula." section="stay" ogImage="/images/sourced/dog-lifestyle-hero-01.webp">
  <main class="article-shell container prose" style="padding: 3rem 0 4rem; max-width: 820px;">
    <p class="label label--accent">Dog-Friendly Peninsula</p>
    <h1>Dog-Friendly Accommodation on the Mornington Peninsula</h1>
    <p><img src="/images/sourced/dog-lifestyle-hero-01.webp" alt="Dog relaxing during a weekend stay" style="width:100%; border-radius: 18px; margin: 0 0 1.5rem; object-fit: cover;" /></p>
    <p>The right dog-friendly stay is not just one that allows pets. It is one that still makes the trip feel worth taking. That means less obsession with pet-policy marketing and more attention to fencing, access, nearby walks, and whether the stay still feels like a Peninsula escape once the dog is in the plan.</p>

    <h2>The filter that matters</h2>
    <ul>
      {rules.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}
    </ul>

    <h2>What the Peninsula does best</h2>
    <ul>
      {stayTypes.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}
    </ul>

    <h2>How to think about booking</h2>
    <p>The strongest Peninsula dog stays are usually houses, cottages, and holiday accommodation rather than traditional hotel inventory. That is partly a policy issue and partly a space issue. Owners should expect to verify fencing, indoor rules, bedding/furniture rules, and any pet fees before committing.</p>

    <h2>Best use cases</h2>
    <p><strong>For beach-first owners:</strong> stay in a zone that keeps Tassells Cove, Somers, or Mornington-side options within easy reach.</p>
    <p><strong>For wine-and-lunch owners:</strong> the right Red Hill / Main Ridge base can work, but only if the property itself is not high-friction with the dog.</p>
    <p><strong>For the easiest overall weekend:</strong> prioritise access and dog practicality over the most prestigious address.</p>

    <p>This page should become a verified shortlist with fencing quality, policy type, and geography explicitly tracked. That is the real difference between a useful dog-stay guide and a shallow booking filter.</p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
